WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.240 --> 00:00:03.960
Foreign

00:00:03.960 --> 00:00:16.260
[Music] I'm Norman Wildberger. Thanks for joining&nbsp;
me. We are in the process of largely outlining&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:16.260 --> 00:00:21.420
a new approach to arithmetic, and today,&nbsp;
a very important and interesting lecture&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:21.420 --> 00:00:27.300
where we try to tackle the problem of how&nbsp;
to create negative numbers in our system.

00:00:29.580 --> 00:00:35.340
So it's quite a long lecture today; there's&nbsp;
quite a lot of stuff in it. I'm going to also&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:35.340 --> 00:00:39.960
say a few philosophical or meta-mathematical&nbsp;
things beforehand to sort of set the stage.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:41.580 --> 00:00:48.540
Also, there's a tentative aspect or an aspect&nbsp;
of this being a proposal. It's not that we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:48.540 --> 00:00:56.520
have a current, valid, logically correct theory&nbsp;
established yet, so we're working towards that.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:57.120 --> 00:01:03.060
There will be an element of exploration today as&nbsp;
we discover things, perhaps for the first time.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:04.980 --> 00:01:11.100
We're going to be introducing negative numbers&nbsp;
from a notion called an anti-multi-set. The&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:11.100 --> 00:01:16.980
basic idea is contained already in a prior&nbsp;
lecture in the Math Foundation series,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:16.980 --> 00:01:24.960
notably Math Foundations 187: The Curious Role of&nbsp;
Nothing in Mathematics and the subsequent videos&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:24.960 --> 00:01:32.400
following that. So what I'm doing today is largely&nbsp;
an extension or modification of what I did there,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:33.120 --> 00:01:38.760
where I already introduced the notion of&nbsp;
anti-objects and the important role of nothing in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:38.760 --> 00:01:45.540
this multi-set framework. We're modifying things&nbsp;
by not having the mark as the central fundamental&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:45.540 --> 00:01:51.720
object but as the empty mset, or zero, as the&nbsp;
fundamental thing. Otherwise, you'll see there's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:51.720 --> 00:01:58.200
a lot of parallel to this. If you're interested&nbsp;
in this situation, which I hope you are, please go&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:58.200 --> 00:02:03.360
and have another view of this video or look at it&nbsp;
for the first time if you haven't already done so.

00:02:04.320 --> 00:02:10.080
Currently, we have a framework that kind of&nbsp;
goes on but starts at a very simple level:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:10.080 --> 00:02:15.660
just the zero multi-set, which is an&nbsp;
empty multi-set. We have natural numbers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:15.660 --> 00:02:23.640
which are just msets of zeros: one, two,&nbsp;
and three. Then we have poly numbers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:23.640 --> 00:02:29.640
which are msets of natural numbers. That one&nbsp;
there is called Alpha Zero. Here's another one;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:30.180 --> 00:02:36.480
it's an mset of natural numbers which we can&nbsp;
interpret as the polynomial 2 plus Alpha Zero&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:36.480 --> 00:02:45.540
plus Alpha Zero cubed. And then multi-sets of poly&nbsp;
numbers like this thing here: this is an mset of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:45.540 --> 00:02:51.600
poly numbers because that's a poly number, that&nbsp;
is, and that is. It has the interpretation of a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:51.600 --> 00:02:59.160
polynomial in more than one variable: Alpha Zero&nbsp;
squared corresponding to that, plus two Alpha One&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:59.160 --> 00:03:05.820
Alpha Two corresponding to these two elements,&nbsp;
plus Alpha Four corresponding to this one. We&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:05.820 --> 00:03:12.600
can go further; we have quite an obvious sort of&nbsp;
inductive or sequential process in extending not&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:12.600 --> 00:03:20.040
just objects but also operations to further levels&nbsp;
down. We also have a nice way of visualizing this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:20.040 --> 00:03:24.360
kind of thing in an alternative way using&nbsp;
trees in the language of computer science.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:26.100 --> 00:03:32.520
Notably, the objects that are appearing here—there&nbsp;
are numbers appearing, but they're all natural&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:32.520 --> 00:03:39.120
numbers. Today, we want to move to try to extend&nbsp;
our number system to include negative numbers.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:40.440 --> 00:03:49.620
That's a very interesting challenge. So broadly,&nbsp;
our aim is to introduce a new number: minus one,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:50.220 --> 00:03:54.660
which I'm also going to write as one&nbsp;
bar. Actually, for a lot of purposes,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:54.660 --> 00:04:00.540
I prefer this bar notation for negative numbers,&nbsp;
and I'm going to largely be following that. I urge&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:00.540 --> 00:04:07.080
you to also consider using that. It's very&nbsp;
useful because then this minus sign is not&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:07.080 --> 00:04:14.100
confused with the subtraction operation, and it&nbsp;
also minimizes the necessary use of brackets in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:14.100 --> 00:04:19.860
a lot of situations. In either case, I'm going to&nbsp;
use one bar. Typically, what we want to establish&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:19.860 --> 00:04:27.300
about this number is that ordinary one plus one&nbsp;
bar equals zero and also that one bar times one&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:27.300 --> 00:04:33.660
bar equals one. Those are two crucial properties&nbsp;
of this new number that we're trying to introduce.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:34.440 --> 00:04:39.780
After we have one bar, we're going to introduce&nbsp;
more general negative numbers so that we get a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:39.780 --> 00:04:45.600
kind of integer number line with the natural&nbsp;
numbers extending to the right like this and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:45.600 --> 00:04:51.660
negative numbers: one bar, two bar, three bar,&nbsp;
etc. We want the usual laws of arithmetic that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:51.660 --> 00:04:57.180
are familiar to us in the natural number domain&nbsp;
to extend to this larger domain of integers.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:58.560 --> 00:05:08.040
Then, as part of this process, we want to extend&nbsp;
these numbers to poly and multi and beyond&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:09.180 --> 00:05:16.200
so that poly numbers and multi numbers and&nbsp;
further things may also use these negative&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:16.200 --> 00:05:20.580
numbers as constituents to build up&nbsp;
these more complicated structures.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:22.140 --> 00:05:28.620
We end up with an extension of the usual laws&nbsp;
of algebra to incorporate negative numbers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:30.540 --> 00:05:34.020
and hopefully, we'll get some&nbsp;
new insights in this way.

00:05:35.400 --> 00:05:40.320
Let me say a few words about negative numbers.&nbsp;
It's important to realize before we start that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:40.320 --> 00:05:50.640
negative numbers have been a source of insecurity,&nbsp;
questioning, and skepticism for a long time.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:51.300 --> 00:05:58.320
Most ancient civilizations, even if they were&nbsp;
reasonably proficient with arithmetic and algebra&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:58.320 --> 00:06:07.380
(for example, even going back to the Babylonians&nbsp;
but also the Greeks, Arabs, and Chinese), had&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:07.380 --> 00:06:14.580
ways of avoiding the explicit usage of negative&nbsp;
numbers. For example, if we want to solve the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:14.580 --> 00:06:21.300
equation x squared plus x minus one equals zero,&nbsp;
that quadratic equation, they would have preferred&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:21.300 --> 00:06:28.140
to rewrite it as x squared plus x equals one&nbsp;
so there are only natural numbers appearing.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:29.160 --> 00:06:35.700
This unsureness about what negative numbers are&nbsp;
and what their role is extends even into the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:35.700 --> 00:06:43.920
modern era. Descartes, Rene Descartes, famously&nbsp;
the father of modern geometry and a key figure in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:43.920 --> 00:06:52.260
17th-century mathematics, was dubious about the&nbsp;
role of negative numbers and explicitly tried to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:52.260 --> 00:06:59.160
avoid them in his geometry. So the usual Cartesian&nbsp;
coordinate axes that we teach undergraduates as&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:59.160 --> 00:07:07.020
being, you know, a result of Descartes' thinking&nbsp;
actually, with its usage of a number line with&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:07.020 --> 00:07:11.820
both positive and negative values, is a little&nbsp;
bit foreign to Descartes' thinking. He preferred&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:11.820 --> 00:07:20.640
to think in terms of having two axes labeled by&nbsp;
positive numbers. So he restricted himself to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:20.640 --> 00:07:27.360
what we might call the sort of upper quadrant. We&nbsp;
have to have some respect for the difficulty in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:27.360 --> 00:07:35.400
establishing a sound theory of integers. You might&nbsp;
like to think personally, just yourself, about how&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:35.400 --> 00:07:41.220
you go about establishing a proper theory&nbsp;
of integers. I know you've all learned&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:41.220 --> 00:07:46.500
about integers somewhere in primary school and&nbsp;
you've sort of been taught these rules, you know,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:46.500 --> 00:07:51.420
and perhaps you can remember back in grade five or&nbsp;
whatever when you were told that minus two times&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:51.420 --> 00:07:59.580
minus three is plus six. Maybe you were asking,&nbsp;
well, if -2 represents a debt, like instead of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:59.580 --> 00:08:04.320
having two apples, I have minus two apples,&nbsp;
meaning that I owe somebody else two apples,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:05.280 --> 00:08:12.480
what does it mean to multiply minus two with minus&nbsp;
three and get plus six? How do we really establish&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:12.480 --> 00:08:19.320
the laws of arithmetic in this integer domain?&nbsp;
Have you actually gone through that yourself?&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:19.320 --> 00:08:25.320
Even if you're a professional mathematician,&nbsp;
chances are you probably haven't. This is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:25.320 --> 00:08:31.740
something that we sort of assume as a&nbsp;
background. We all have faith in this,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:31.740 --> 00:08:38.580
but do we actually have a coherent theory? That's&nbsp;
the starting point here. We have to recognize&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:38.580 --> 00:08:44.280
that there's something potentially problematic or&nbsp;
difficult or challenging about negative numbers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:44.280 --> 00:08:50.820
and today I'm going to be challenging you&nbsp;
further by introducing them to you in a very&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:50.820 --> 00:09:01.680
novel way that, surprisingly, ultimately relies on&nbsp;
20th-century physics for its intellectual support.

00:09:01.680 --> 00:09:09.600
So let's begin our exploration and try to deduce&nbsp;
what likely we have to have if we want to have a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:09.600 --> 00:09:15.240
consistent theory of negative numbers extending&nbsp;
this multi-set arithmetic that we already have.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:16.680 --> 00:09:23.100
The primary thing that we're aiming for is, first&nbsp;
of all, a minus one or a one bar. Let me remind&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:23.100 --> 00:09:29.340
you that in our system, the number one is the mset&nbsp;
consisting of zero, and zero, of course, is the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:29.340 --> 00:09:38.940
empty mset. This new thing that we're interested&nbsp;
in, this minus one or one bar, is also going to be&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:38.940 --> 00:09:46.620
an mset because all of the things in our world so&nbsp;
far are msets. So we posit that this is a new mset&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:46.620 --> 00:09:53.400
with something in it, but we don't know what that&nbsp;
thing is that's inside here. So let's represent it&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:54.720 --> 00:10:01.980
with a question mark. What do we need to happen?&nbsp;
We want that one plus one bar is zero. So one,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:01.980 --> 00:10:08.880
that's the mset zero. One bar is this mset with&nbsp;
a question mark in it. We have to add these two&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:08.880 --> 00:10:14.460
things. How do you add msets? Well, you dump them&nbsp;
both out into another mset. So we're creating a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:14.460 --> 00:10:19.620
new mset, and the zero goes in that mset, and this&nbsp;
question mark, whatever it is, also goes in there.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:21.060 --> 00:10:31.440
We want the result of that to be zero, which&nbsp;
is the empty mset. So this question mark has&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:31.440 --> 00:10:39.960
to have the property that if you put it in&nbsp;
a box with zero, the result is an empty box.

00:10:42.120 --> 00:10:49.860
That's necessarily what's required in our&nbsp;
framework. There's no getting around it. This&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:49.860 --> 00:10:58.980
is a very unfamiliar situation to mathematics&nbsp;
in the last 10,000 years. There's nothing in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:58.980 --> 00:11:06.480
mathematics that's really like this that gives us&nbsp;
any kind of prior intuition about such a thing. We&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:06.480 --> 00:11:11.340
don't have situations where we have one thing&nbsp;
being completely canceled with something else&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:11.340 --> 00:11:18.540
to create nothing. Not zero, but nothing. This&nbsp;
zero and this question mark are creating nothing.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:21.300 --> 00:11:32.700
But 20th-century physics, completely remarkably,&nbsp;
has discovered such a phenomenon. Crucially,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:32.700 --> 00:11:41.460
it's one of the most important developments of&nbsp;
20th-century physics: the discovery by Paul Dirac&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:42.060 --> 00:11:50.100
of anti-particles, starting with the anti-particle&nbsp;
for the electron, which is called the positron.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:50.880 --> 00:11:56.640
It's a particle that is very similar to the&nbsp;
electron in most aspects—it has the same mass,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:56.640 --> 00:12:04.740
same spin, that kind of thing—but crucially,&nbsp;
it has opposite charge. Moreover, it has this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:04.740 --> 00:12:11.160
property that if an electron and a positron&nbsp;
get close together, they mutually annihilate&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:11.160 --> 00:12:17.340
each other in a flash of light with some&nbsp;
photons being emitted. They have rest energy;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:17.340 --> 00:12:23.820
that energy has to go somewhere, and the energy&nbsp;
is carried off by two photons going in opposite&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:23.820 --> 00:12:30.120
directions so that linear momentum is conserved.&nbsp;
This is a totally remarkable thing, especially&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:30.120 --> 00:12:36.000
when it became clear that this is not just a&nbsp;
phenomenon involving electrons and positrons.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:36.600 --> 00:12:43.860
The positron was found a few years after&nbsp;
Dirac postulated its existence. Moreover,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:43.860 --> 00:12:52.620
and sort of spectacularly, it's now the case&nbsp;
that it appears that almost every particle that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:52.620 --> 00:12:59.220
is known—all these elementary particles—has&nbsp;
corresponding antiparticles which essentially&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:59.220 --> 00:13:04.200
have the same kind of relation. They more or&nbsp;
less share most of the properties with the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:04.200 --> 00:13:09.060
original particles, except that when you&nbsp;
bring two of them together, the particle&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:09.060 --> 00:13:15.300
and the anti-particle mutually annihilate&nbsp;
each other, releasing some kind of energy.

00:13:18.240 --> 00:13:22.320
This is a remarkable thing, and I have to say&nbsp;
more about that, but that's really our motivating&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:22.320 --> 00:13:30.720
idea. This is exactly what we're needing here,&nbsp;
minus the energy transmission. Zero combined&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:30.720 --> 00:13:38.160
with something gives us nothing. So we're going to&nbsp;
introduce such a new object into our mathematics.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:39.780 --> 00:13:46.920
We have to create an anti-particle for&nbsp;
our fundamental object, which is zero,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:46.920 --> 00:13:54.060
the empty mset. I'm going to give it the name zero&nbsp;
with an "a" above it, "a" of course standing for&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:54.840 --> 00:14:00.300
anti-particle. We're going to call it&nbsp;
anti-zero. The anti-zero is this expression;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:00.300 --> 00:14:10.800
it's a new symbol, with the property that if&nbsp;
you have an mset containing zero and zero-a,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:12.960 --> 00:14:18.900
they mutually cancel each other&nbsp;
out, and we just get an empty mset.

00:14:20.760 --> 00:14:26.700
So the question is, well, what actually is this&nbsp;
thing? We're not going to answer that question any&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:26.700 --> 00:14:35.040
more than to say, well, it is only a symbol. We're&nbsp;
dealing with a language of symbols, and just like&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:35.040 --> 00:14:40.680
this is a sort of symbol, this is a new symbol&nbsp;
that we're introducing so that we're able to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:40.680 --> 00:14:48.240
ultimately come up with a minus one. It's pretty&nbsp;
well necessary if we're going to do arithmetic&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:48.240 --> 00:14:57.000
in this multi-set framework. Curiously, if this&nbsp;
arithmetic had been discovered centuries earlier,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:57.000 --> 00:15:05.640
then probably the physicists would have been much&nbsp;
more inclined to discover the anti-particle kind&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:05.640 --> 00:15:12.600
of symmetry that exists in nature, which is such a&nbsp;
profound and remarkable symmetry, perhaps earlier.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:13.920 --> 00:15:18.420
Along the lines of the physics, I do have to&nbsp;
remark one more additional thing, however,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:18.420 --> 00:15:26.580
that this symmetry we have is a broken symmetry in&nbsp;
that the actual world we live in is predominantly&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:26.580 --> 00:15:33.000
made out of matter particles and not antimatter.&nbsp;
Antimatter is something that we only can cook up&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:33.540 --> 00:15:39.180
under rather extreme circumstances or perhaps in&nbsp;
cosmic rays or something, but it's not typical.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:39.180 --> 00:15:44.700
At least as far as we can see, everywhere we&nbsp;
look, we see matter, not a lot of antimatter.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:46.440 --> 00:15:53.160
So this imbalance between the matter and the&nbsp;
antimatter is a huge problem for physicists&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:53.160 --> 00:16:00.000
and cosmologists. It's one of the central problems&nbsp;
in 21st-century physics: to explain this apparent&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:00.000 --> 00:16:07.140
asymmetry between these two kinds of things,&nbsp;
which otherwise seem to be quite parallel.

00:16:07.740 --> 00:16:13.020
Now I want to explore with you some consequences&nbsp;
of this fundamental idea of having this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:13.560 --> 00:16:21.600
somewhat symmetrical object anti-zero added&nbsp;
to our arithmetic. We're going to develop some&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:21.600 --> 00:16:29.280
consequences, but I want to emphasize that this is&nbsp;
in an exploratory fashion. We do not know actually&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:29.280 --> 00:16:35.340
if this proposed arithmetic that I'm laying out&nbsp;
here for you actually is a consistent arithmetic.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:35.340 --> 00:16:41.400
We do not know that. We would like that to&nbsp;
be true, and maybe there are some indications&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:41.400 --> 00:16:46.500
that it might be, but this is still a very&nbsp;
important question, and we can't get around it.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:47.760 --> 00:16:53.160
In particular, what we are definitely not&nbsp;
allowed to do is what the modern analysts do&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:53.160 --> 00:16:58.860
with respect to real numbers, which is basically&nbsp;
to say, well, we don't actually have a proper&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:58.860 --> 00:17:04.680
foundation for real numbers, so let's just stomp&nbsp;
our feet and sort of axiomatically suppose that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:04.680 --> 00:17:09.180
we have a set of real numbers that obey the&nbsp;
following pleasant properties that we would&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:09.180 --> 00:17:16.500
like to have happen. We are not allowed to do&nbsp;
that. We have to establish everything correctly&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:16.500 --> 00:17:23.880
in a bona fide way. There's a lot of work to&nbsp;
be done here in first of all checking whether&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:23.880 --> 00:17:28.800
or not what I'm proposing actually makes sense,&nbsp;
and maybe it doesn't. It may be one of you will&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:28.800 --> 00:17:34.500
next week discover some contradiction. It's&nbsp;
possible. I'll wear that. That'll be fun;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:34.500 --> 00:17:39.840
then we can revamp things or look in an alternate&nbsp;
direction or see how we have to modify things.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:41.280 --> 00:17:47.820
But we're not just going to assume that what&nbsp;
we want to be true is going to be true just&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:47.820 --> 00:17:52.440
because we want it to be. Sorry, analysts,&nbsp;
but we want to do things correctly here.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:53.880 --> 00:18:02.220
So let's proceed with some possible&nbsp;
implications of the existence of this anti-zero.

00:18:02.220 --> 00:18:08.520
Let's look at this equation: one times zero equals&nbsp;
zero, which is a valid equation in our system so&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:08.520 --> 00:18:16.440
far. We want that still to be valid. This is a&nbsp;
basic idea that all of the prior arithmetical&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:16.440 --> 00:18:22.140
rules that we currently have for the objects that&nbsp;
we currently have, we want them still to be valid&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:22.140 --> 00:18:26.880
even when we're extending the arithmetic&nbsp;
to include these new kinds of objects.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:29.340 --> 00:18:36.120
Here is one; it's the empty set contained in&nbsp;
the set, and zero, of course, is the empty set.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:37.320 --> 00:18:46.560
Now crucially, this empty mset can be replaced&nbsp;
with the mset consisting of zero and anti-zero.

00:18:47.960 --> 00:18:54.300
This is like what the physicists call&nbsp;
particle-antiparticle creation. This is an&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:54.300 --> 00:19:02.460
important idea that to the physicist, nothing like&nbsp;
a vacuum is not exactly completely empty because,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:02.460 --> 00:19:09.720
bubbling out of the vacuum, you can create these&nbsp;
particle-antiparticle pairs just like we're doing&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:09.720 --> 00:19:16.320
here. This is very parallel to roughly the&nbsp;
kinds of things that they're doing. This has&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:16.320 --> 00:19:22.680
to still be a reasonable rule. What happens&nbsp;
when we apply the usual laws for multiplying&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:22.680 --> 00:19:27.480
this thing by this? Well, the usual law is&nbsp;
that we should take the mset consisting of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:27.480 --> 00:19:35.340
sums of elements here and elements here, so that&nbsp;
would be zero plus zero and zero plus anti-zero.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:36.660 --> 00:19:41.460
Zero plus zero is zero, and zero plus&nbsp;
anti-zero, we don't know what that is yet,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:42.300 --> 00:19:46.920
but we do know that the result of this&nbsp;
thing had better be the right-hand side,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:46.920 --> 00:19:57.480
which is the empty set. So this object, zero&nbsp;
plus zero-a or zero plus anti-zero, had better&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:57.480 --> 00:20:06.000
be anti-zero because we want it to cancel with&nbsp;
this zero to get nothing. So we get a rule:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:07.380 --> 00:20:14.280
zero plus anti-zero is anti-zero, and if we&nbsp;
did it the other way around, symmetrically,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:14.280 --> 00:20:22.500
anti-zero plus zero is anti-zero. There we have a&nbsp;
first rule of arithmetic combining this new object&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:22.500 --> 00:20:29.580
anti-zero with a prior object zero. Let me remind&nbsp;
you that this is sort of consistent with the way&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:29.580 --> 00:20:34.860
we think zero works: when we take zero and we&nbsp;
add it to something, we get that other something.

00:20:36.180 --> 00:20:40.500
Here's another rule that we want to&nbsp;
have satisfied: zero times zero is zero.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:41.280 --> 00:20:48.480
Empty mset times empty mset should equal empty&nbsp;
mset. But this empty mset can be thought of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:48.480 --> 00:20:56.160
as the mset 0-anti-zero. Similarly, this one is&nbsp;
zero-anti-zero. When we think about it this way,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:56.160 --> 00:21:02.640
to multiply those two, we have to form all&nbsp;
possible pairs and add them. So we have to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:02.640 --> 00:21:09.420
have zero plus zero as one entry, zero plus&nbsp;
anti-zero as another entry, anti-zero plus zero&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:09.420 --> 00:21:17.040
as another entry, and anti-zero plus anti-zero&nbsp;
as another entry. Zero plus zero is zero. Zero&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:17.040 --> 00:21:22.200
plus anti-zero, we've just established that's&nbsp;
anti-zero. This one here is also anti-zero.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:23.580 --> 00:21:29.940
But anti-zero plus anti-zero, we don't know&nbsp;
yet what that is. Nevertheless, we can do some&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:29.940 --> 00:21:36.060
cancellations because this zero and this anti-zero&nbsp;
are together in this mset, so they are going to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:36.060 --> 00:21:41.940
mutually annihilate each other, so they're gone.&nbsp;
What we have left is a single anti-zero there,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:42.600 --> 00:21:49.500
and this combination anti-zero plus anti-zero.&nbsp;
Hopefully, we're going to get the right-hand side,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:49.500 --> 00:21:57.900
which is the empty mset. Again, we must have some&nbsp;
mutual cancellation. We have an anti-zero here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:57.900 --> 00:22:04.920
so this thing here had better be zero because&nbsp;
that's the thing that annihilates with anti-zero&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:04.920 --> 00:22:11.700
to get nothing. So we can conclude that&nbsp;
anti-zero plus anti-zero equals zero.

00:22:13.380 --> 00:22:17.640
For our next derivation, let's do something&nbsp;
similar to what we just did but a little bit&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:17.640 --> 00:22:25.560
more generally. Let's consider an mset consisting&nbsp;
of some object M, where M is some mset or object&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:25.560 --> 00:22:31.980
in this arithmetic. We're again multiplying it by&nbsp;
zero. Typically, we want that to be zero. That's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:31.980 --> 00:22:40.440
what we sort of expect. In terms of msets, there's&nbsp;
mset M. Zero is, of course, just the empty mset,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:40.440 --> 00:22:45.000
and that again can be replaced with the&nbsp;
mset consisting of zero and anti-zero.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:45.600 --> 00:22:49.740
So when we now do this multiplication, we get&nbsp;
something similar as before but a little bit&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:49.740 --> 00:22:55.080
more generally. We get M plus zero as one of&nbsp;
the entries, and M plus anti-zero as the other&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:55.080 --> 00:23:02.700
entry. M plus zero is M, and here we have M plus&nbsp;
anti-zero. The right-hand side ought to be the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:02.700 --> 00:23:12.420
empty set, so we see that for any mset or object M&nbsp;
in this arithmetic, if this is going to be valid,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:13.020 --> 00:23:21.600
then there has to be an object that cancels M&nbsp;
in the same way that anti-zero cancels zero.

00:23:25.320 --> 00:23:32.940
This is a huge extension. We are&nbsp;
necessarily forced to recognize that this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:33.540 --> 00:23:39.300
particle-antiparticle symmetry extends&nbsp;
far beyond the zero-anti-zero pairing,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:40.080 --> 00:23:48.060
just like Dirac's electron-positron kind of&nbsp;
symmetry actually ended up extending much further,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:48.060 --> 00:23:55.500
to in fact general particles. In fact, these&nbsp;
days, it's recognized that that's valid even&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:56.400 --> 00:24:01.140
at the atomic level and, in principle, even at&nbsp;
the molecular level and even at the level of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:01.140 --> 00:24:07.680
human beings. It's possible that there could be an&nbsp;
anti-Norman, exactly more or less the same as me,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:07.680 --> 00:24:14.640
but made entirely of antiparticles. The same&nbsp;
kind of thing is happening here. We have this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:14.640 --> 00:24:22.920
big enlargement of this symmetry, with this&nbsp;
divide between matter and antimatter at the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:22.920 --> 00:24:29.100
physical level, between msets and these&nbsp;
anti-msets in this arithmetical framework.

00:24:30.480 --> 00:24:36.540
What should we call this thing? Well, obviously&nbsp;
we should call it M with a superscript a. We'll&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:36.540 --> 00:24:44.820
call it anti-M. We want this anti-M to have the&nbsp;
property that if you have M and anti-M in an mset,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:44.820 --> 00:24:51.240
like they're just objects in an mset, they&nbsp;
find each other and they cancel; they're gone,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:51.240 --> 00:25:05.880
and we just get nothing inside this empty mset.&nbsp;
What we've established up here is that this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:05.880 --> 00:25:14.580
particular combination, capital M plus anti-zero,&nbsp;
is going to be this anti-M. In other words,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:14.580 --> 00:25:21.900
this anti-M is actually M plus anti-zero. We&nbsp;
could do it another way around: anti-zero plus M.

00:25:25.200 --> 00:25:27.960
In particular, if you have&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:29.040 --> 00:25:36.300
M being anti-zero, you play the same game with&nbsp;
anti-zero, which is an object in our world,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:36.960 --> 00:25:45.540
then the anti of the anti-zero should be zero&nbsp;
because if we replace M here with anti-zero,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:45.540 --> 00:25:51.660
then over here we have anti-zero plus anti-zero,&nbsp;
which we've just established is zero. So that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:51.660 --> 00:25:58.320
establishes that if we take the anti of zero and&nbsp;
then we take the anti of that, in the following&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:58.320 --> 00:26:02.700
sense that I've just described, then we're going&nbsp;
to get back zero. Now I'm going to play a very&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:02.700 --> 00:26:09.000
similar game to the previous ones, except that&nbsp;
I'm going to move up or down in the operation&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:09.000 --> 00:26:14.100
ladder. Instead of thinking about multiplication,&nbsp;
I'm going to think about the carrot operation.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:15.420 --> 00:26:21.120
Let's look at the equation one carrot zero equals&nbsp;
zero, which is a valid equation in our system.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:24.600 --> 00:26:28.800
If it's a valid equation, then it should&nbsp;
still be valid after we replace the empty&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:28.800 --> 00:26:37.140
set here on the left-hand side with the set&nbsp;
0-anti-zero. When we do this carrot operation,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:37.140 --> 00:26:42.660
let me remind you that what we're doing is we&nbsp;
take all possible pairs and we have to multiply&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:42.660 --> 00:26:49.020
them. So we have to take zero times zero and&nbsp;
zero times anti-zero. Zero times zero is zero,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:49.020 --> 00:26:58.800
so this thing here, again, since we want this to&nbsp;
be zero (maybe I should write that we want this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:58.800 --> 00:27:07.500
to be zero), it follows that this combination,&nbsp;
zero times anti-zero, had better be anti-zero.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:08.880 --> 00:27:16.920
And the other way around, anti-zero times zero&nbsp;
equals anti-zero. I've put triple exclamation&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:16.920 --> 00:27:26.520
marks here, so please make note of this. This&nbsp;
is an unfamiliar aspect of this arithmetic. So&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:26.520 --> 00:27:31.500
perhaps some of you are getting a little bit&nbsp;
nervous, and this is a cause for pause here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:31.500 --> 00:27:40.740
because we are declaring that we have some object&nbsp;
so that when we multiply it by zero, we do not get&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:40.740 --> 00:27:49.020
zero anymore. Usually, that's always what happens:&nbsp;
when you multiply by zero, you get zero. But here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:49.020 --> 00:27:56.640
in this world, it appears that zero times&nbsp;
anti-zero is not zero; it's rather anti-zero.

00:27:59.520 --> 00:28:04.380
We can do the same kind of thing, replacing the&nbsp;
one with zero. Zero carrot zero equals zero. That&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:04.380 --> 00:28:09.960
gives us this equation. We do the multiplications:&nbsp;
zero times zero, zero times zero-a, zero-a,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:09.960 --> 00:28:24.300
zero-a, zero to the a, zero to the a. Zero times&nbsp;
anti-zero, we've just established, is anti-zero.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:24.300 --> 00:28:32.400
This one's also anti-zero. We've just established&nbsp;
that these two here can be determined because now,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:32.400 --> 00:28:39.720
again, these cancel. We just get anti-zero,&nbsp;
and this anti-zero times anti-zero. Since we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:39.720 --> 00:28:45.960
want that to be the empty mset, we must have&nbsp;
that this combination is actually the thing&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:45.960 --> 00:28:52.380
that cancels anti-zero, which is zero. So we&nbsp;
get anti-zero times anti-zero equals zero.

00:28:55.380 --> 00:29:00.420
So we have two things multiplying&nbsp;
together, basically squaring to get zero,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:00.420 --> 00:29:08.400
but the actual object itself is not zero.&nbsp;
It's another sort of unpredictable thing,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:11.880 --> 00:29:16.620
counter to our usual intuition. Great. So now we&nbsp;
can write down addition and multiplication tables&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:16.620 --> 00:29:25.320
for zero, the zero level of our arithmetic, which&nbsp;
now contains not just zero but also anti-zero. So&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:25.320 --> 00:29:32.940
at that zeroth level, there are now two objects.&nbsp;
There's an addition table: zero plus zero is zero,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:32.940 --> 00:29:39.300
zero plus anti-zero is anti-zero, anti-zero plus&nbsp;
zero is anti-zero, and anti-zero plus anti-zero&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:39.300 --> 00:29:47.640
is zero. And there is a multiplication table:&nbsp;
zero times zero is zero, zero times anti-zero&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:47.640 --> 00:29:56.400
is anti-zero, anti-zero times zero is anti-zero,&nbsp;
and anti-zero times anti-zero is zero. Notably,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:57.960 --> 00:30:05.940
these tables are pretty well the same except for&nbsp;
the operation sign. They're exactly the same. So&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:05.940 --> 00:30:12.720
at the level of zero, the operations of addition&nbsp;
and multiplication cannot be distinguished.

00:30:17.880 --> 00:30:23.280
Here's another exercise if you like this kind of&nbsp;
thing. Show that for any mset or object M which&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:23.280 --> 00:30:33.000
is not equal to anti-zero, we have M times&nbsp;
anti-zero, the same as anti-zero times M, is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:33.540 --> 00:30:41.160
anti-zero. This is quite interesting because of&nbsp;
this requirement here that we have to restrict&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:41.160 --> 00:30:48.480
ourselves. It's not true; this is not true&nbsp;
if M is equal to anti-zero itself because&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:48.480 --> 00:30:54.840
if M is equal to anti-zero, anti-zero times&nbsp;
anti-zero, that's equal to zero, not anti-zero.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:57.120 --> 00:31:05.820
So that's already suggesting that that's quite an&nbsp;
interesting sort of thing. We have to be mindful&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:05.820 --> 00:31:12.060
of this sort of exemption to this general rule.&nbsp;
There's something interesting happening here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:12.060 --> 00:31:20.760
and it motivates us to really investigate further&nbsp;
the internal consistency of this arithmetic. Is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:20.760 --> 00:31:26.940
this arithmetic really consistent or not? Having&nbsp;
spent quite a lot of time on these anti-zeros&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:26.940 --> 00:31:32.580
and their various properties, now let's move to&nbsp;
negative numbers. That's a different kettle of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:32.580 --> 00:31:41.280
fish because we are still using the anti property&nbsp;
but sort of putting it one level down in an mset.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:41.280 --> 00:31:46.080
Specifically, what we're going to do now is&nbsp;
introduce minus one, or preferably one bar,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:47.040 --> 00:31:56.100
defined as the mset consisting of anti-zero. Let&nbsp;
me remind you that one is the mset consisting of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:56.100 --> 00:32:02.580
zero. So now minus one is the mset consisting of&nbsp;
anti-zero. If we add the two of them, well then,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:02.580 --> 00:32:08.220
obviously, we get an mset consisting of an&nbsp;
anti-zero and a zero. They annihilate, and we just&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:08.220 --> 00:32:13.740
get the empty set. So yes, indeed, one bar plus&nbsp;
one, or one plus one bar in the other way around,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:13.740 --> 00:32:21.180
is indeed zero. This fundamental property that we&nbsp;
require for a minus one, or one bar, is satisfied.

00:32:22.140 --> 00:32:30.120
Let's look at one bar times one. There's one bar,&nbsp;
there's one. We're multiplying, so we have to take&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:30.120 --> 00:32:38.220
all possible sums of elements. We have an mset&nbsp;
with anti-zero plus zero. We know that sum is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:38.220 --> 00:32:45.000
anti-zero, and so we see that minus one times one&nbsp;
is minus one. Similarly, one times minus one is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:45.000 --> 00:32:51.300
one. In the same spirit, minus one times minus&nbsp;
one. There's minus one, there's minus one. We&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:51.300 --> 00:32:56.400
multiply them, we get anti-zero plus anti-zero&nbsp;
inside. We know that particular combination is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:56.400 --> 00:33:03.900
zero, okay, we've already established that. So&nbsp;
we get that one bar times one bar equals one.

00:33:04.920 --> 00:33:10.620
Now that we have minus one, or one bar, we can&nbsp;
introduce integers or negative numbers. First,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:11.520 --> 00:33:18.540
definition: if N is a natural number, then&nbsp;
N-bar, otherwise known as minus N, is going to be&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:18.540 --> 00:33:28.260
defined by one bar times N. For example, 2-bar by&nbsp;
definition is one bar times two. There's one bar,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:29.220 --> 00:33:36.300
the mset consisting of anti-zero. Here's two, the&nbsp;
mset consisting of zero zero. We multiply them,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:36.300 --> 00:33:42.480
so we have to form anti-zero plus zero,&nbsp;
anti-zero plus zero. Each of those is anti-zero,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:42.480 --> 00:33:51.600
so we get anti-zero, anti-zero. That's what&nbsp;
2-bar is as an mset. It's the mset consisting&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:51.600 --> 00:33:59.460
of two anti-zeros in a parallel way to the fact&nbsp;
that two is the mset consisting of two zeros.

00:34:02.040 --> 00:34:09.480
Let's do some arithmetic with integers, say two&nbsp;
plus three bar. So there's two, there's three bar,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:09.480 --> 00:34:17.340
or negative three. Adding the msets, we just&nbsp;
dump them all together, so we get a zero, a zero,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:17.340 --> 00:34:22.440
anti-zero, anti-zero, anti-zero. We get some&nbsp;
cancellation because they're in the same mset, so&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:22.440 --> 00:34:28.620
they can interact with each other. This zero, that&nbsp;
anti-zero, perhaps they annihilate. This zero,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:28.620 --> 00:34:36.600
that anti-zero, perhaps they annihilate. We end up&nbsp;
with a single anti-zero in the mset, so that's one&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:36.600 --> 00:34:43.740
bar, or minus one. Two times three bar, well,&nbsp;
there's two times three bar. We're taking the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:43.740 --> 00:34:50.520
product, so we have to form all possible pairs and&nbsp;
form their sums. Zero plus anti-zero, well, that's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:50.520 --> 00:34:58.740
anti-zero. All of these are anti-zero. We get&nbsp;
six anti-zeros, which is six bar, or minus six.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:59.940 --> 00:35:05.760
You can kind of see that the usual arithmetical&nbsp;
laws for integers are going to be satisfied here.

00:35:07.920 --> 00:35:13.980
In particular, why minus two times minus&nbsp;
three is six is going to be self-evident&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:13.980 --> 00:35:19.200
simply because anti-zero plus anti-zero is zero.

00:35:20.160 --> 00:35:25.440
In our final slide, I want to show you that&nbsp;
this notion of negation actually now extends&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:25.440 --> 00:35:30.780
much further. Usually in algebra, when we&nbsp;
introduce negative things, we have to sort&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:30.780 --> 00:35:35.580
of do it separately at various levels. When we&nbsp;
introduce polynomials, we have to define how we're&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:35.580 --> 00:35:44.280
going to define negative multiplications, etc.&nbsp;
Here, essentially, the same point of view that we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:44.280 --> 00:35:52.980
already have allows us to extend this negativity&nbsp;
all the way down. Again, we have to draw heavily&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:52.980 --> 00:36:01.620
upon this prior understanding of anti-msets.&nbsp;
Suppose M is an arbitrary pure mset, so it's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:01.620 --> 00:36:07.860
an mset just consisting of things that we already&nbsp;
are working with, no other kinds of mathematical&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:07.860 --> 00:36:16.080
objects. We're going to define M-bar, or minus&nbsp;
M if you like, just to be one bar times M.

00:36:19.440 --> 00:36:29.820
Now we can deduce that if M is a pure mset,&nbsp;
then what this really is doing is taking the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:29.820 --> 00:36:37.080
anti of each of the elements of M. So M&nbsp;
is a box that has a lot of little boxes&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:37.080 --> 00:36:41.760
inside. These are the elements. Those boxes&nbsp;
themselves may very well have all kinds of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:41.760 --> 00:36:48.660
stuff inside each one of them. That's fine.&nbsp;
But the negative of the entire big box is,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:48.660 --> 00:36:53.340
according to this, what you get when you&nbsp;
consider the box consisting of the antis&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:53.340 --> 00:36:58.620
of each of the elements: the anti of this&nbsp;
little element, the anti of this element,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:58.620 --> 00:37:04.680
the anti of this little element, and so on.&nbsp;
That's what the negative of the entire mset is.

00:37:05.940 --> 00:37:10.560
Why is that? Well, M-bar, according&nbsp;
to the definition, is one bar times M.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:10.560 --> 00:37:17.040
One bar, there it is, the mset consisting of&nbsp;
anti-zero. M is the mset consisting of, let's say,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:17.040 --> 00:37:24.120
little M's where M is an m. We have a whole bunch&nbsp;
of these elements of M. How do we multiply things?&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:24.660 --> 00:37:30.660
We have to take all possible pairs between these&nbsp;
guys and these guys, and we have to add them.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:30.660 --> 00:37:36.540
Well, there's only one of them here, so we're&nbsp;
just taking all pairs of the form O-A and M,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:36.540 --> 00:37:43.860
and we're adding them. We're getting O-A&nbsp;
plus M as we run little M through capital M.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:44.880 --> 00:37:53.820
But O-A plus M, if M is any mset, is the&nbsp;
anti of M. Remember, that was one of the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:53.820 --> 00:38:01.200
rules we established, that you add anti-zero to&nbsp;
anything, you're getting the anti of that thing.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:02.520 --> 00:38:10.140
So each of the elements of M is being anti-ed&nbsp;
by the effect of multiplying by minus one.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:11.520 --> 00:38:14.400
That's another way of thinking about&nbsp;
what negation is in this world.

00:38:17.220 --> 00:38:23.640
It's unfamiliar; it's something that we need&nbsp;
to get our heads around. In my next video,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:23.640 --> 00:38:27.360
I'm going to try to give you some more&nbsp;
illustrations of how this works. There's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:27.360 --> 00:38:31.440
much more to be said here. This has all&nbsp;
kinds of very interesting consequences,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:32.400 --> 00:38:37.380
and there's still exploration to be made in&nbsp;
terms of whether this actually rings true&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:37.380 --> 00:38:44.340
and is a consistent theory, which we do not&nbsp;
yet know. This is a prospective arithmetic.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:44.340 --> 00:38:50.820
There is much to investigate and think about&nbsp;
here. I'm Norman Wildberger Thanks for listening.

00:38:50.820 --> 00:38:51.276
[Music]

